trans-unit.source: Specifies whether the global HTTP poll-interval setting overrides the object-level Cpoll-interval setting.
Specifies whether the global HTTP sampling-rate setting overrides the object-level sampling-rate setting.
Specifies whether the global interface poll-interval setting overrides the object-level poll-interval setting.
Specifies whether the group should be present or absent.
Specifies whether the httponly attribute should be enabled or disabled for the inserted cookies.
Specifies whether the instance is optimized for EBS I/O (true) or not (false).
Specifies whether the instance should be automatically restarted if it is terminated by Compute Engine (not terminated by a user).
Specifies whether the interface is a Layer 2 sub-interface.
Specifies whether the module waits until the cluster is active or deleted before moving on. It takes "usually less than 10 minutes" per AWS documentation.
Specifies whether the module waits until the distribution has completed processing the creation or update.
Specifies whether the monitor operates in reverse mode.
Specifies whether the monitor operates in reverse mode. When the monitor is in reverse mode, a successful check marks the monitored object down instead of up.
Specifies whether the monitor operates in transparent mode.
Specifies whether the monitor sends error messages and additional information to a log file created and labeled specifically for this monitor.
Specifies whether the network interface should be created with the accelerated networking feature or not.
Specifies whether the non-ssl Redis server port (6379) is enabled.
Specifies whether the pool-name in the inserted BIG-IP default cookie should be encrypted.
Specifies whether the record applies to IPv4 or IPv6 addresses.
Specifies whether the responder's certificate is checked for an OCSP signing extension.
Specifies whether the secure attribute should be enabled or disabled for the inserted cookies.
Specifies whether the security policy logs the request data in the Statistics screen
Specifies whether the subnet should be present or absent.
Specifies whether the system accepts ARP requests.

Specifies whether the system accepts ARP requests. When (disabled), specifies that the system does not accept ARP requests. Note that both ARP and ICMP Echo must be disabled in order for forwarding virtual servers using that virtual address to forward ICMP packets. If (enabled), then the packets are dropped.
Specifies whether the system answers DNS queries for the default zones localhost, reverse 127.0.0.1 and ::1, and AS112.
Specifies whether the system answers and issues TCP-formatted queries.
Specifies whether the system answers and issues UDP-formatted queries.
Specifies whether the system answers zone transfer requests for a DNS zone created on the system.
Specifies whether the system applies Nagle's algorithm to reduce the number of short segments on the network.
Specifies whether the system auto-discovers the links for this server.
Specifies whether the system auto-discovers the links for this server. When creating a new GTM server, if this parameter is not specified, the default value disabled is used.
Specifies whether the system auto-discovers the virtual servers for this server. When creating a new GTM server, if this parameter is not specified, the default value disabled is used.
Specifies whether the system automatically changes the status of a resource to enabled at the next successful monitor check.
Specifies whether the system automatically changes the status of a resource to up at the next successful monitor check.
Specifies whether the system automatically creates ephemeral nodes using the IP addresses returned by the resolution of a DNS query for a node defined by an FQDN.

Specifies whether the system automatically deletes the virtual address with the deletion of the last associated virtual server. When disabled, specifies that the system leaves the virtual address even when all associated virtual servers have been deleted. When creating the virtual address, the default value is enabled.

Specifies whether the system caches DNS lookups or performs the operation each time a lookup is needed. Please note that this applies only to Access Policy Manager features, such as ACLs, web application rewrites, and authentication.
Specifies whether the system caches DNS responses.
Specifies whether the system can use IPv4 to query backend nameservers.
Specifies whether the system can use IPv6 to query backend nameservers.
Specifies whether the system checks an SSL peer, as a result of which the system requires and verifies the server certificate.
Specifies whether the system displays an advisory message on the login screen.
Specifies whether the system enforces cross-routing restrictions or not.
Specifies whether the system forwards non-wide IP queries to the local BIND server on the BIG-IP system.
Specifies whether the system load balances traffic according to the priority number assigned to the pool member.
Specifies whether the system preserves the source port of the connection.
Specifies whether the system requires TLS for communications between specified senders and recipients.
Specifies whether the system rewrites the URIs that are part of HTTP redirect (3XX) responses
Specifies whether the system rewrites the URIs that are part of HTTP redirect (3XX) responses.
Specifies whether the system signs responses with DNSSEC keys and replies to DNSSEC specific queries (e.g., DNSKEY query type).
Specifies whether the system synchronizes the entire configuration during synchronization operations.
Specifies whether the system uses Global Traffic Manager to manage the response.
Specifies whether the system uses an SSL port to communicate with the LDAP server.
Specifies whether the system uses enhanced loss recovery to recover from random packet losses more effectively.
Specifies whether the system uses route advertisement for this virtual address.
Specifies whether the system verifies the identity of the authoritative nameserver that sends updated information for this DNS Express zone.
Specifies whether the target must include attributes in its response to be considered up.
Specifies whether the traffic group fails back to the default device.
Specifies whether the traffic group fails back to the initial device specified in ha_order.
Specifies whether the traffic group fails back to the initial device specified in ha_order
Specifies whether the user has configured the BIG-IP system to remember a password on a specific computer and how many passwords to remember.
Specifies whether this DNS Express zone is a DNS response policy zone (RPZ).

Specifies whether this is a key signing key (KSK) or a zone signing key (ZSK). Key signing keys have the Secure Entry Point flag set and, when active, will only be used to sign resource record sets of type DNSKEY. Zone signing keys do not have the Secure Entry Point flag set and will be used to sign all other types of resource record sets. .
Specifies whether this system is a member of a synchronization group.
Specifies whether to Remove, Preserve, or Append Via headers included in a client request to an origin web server.
Specifies whether to Remove, Preserve, or Append Via headers included in an origin web server response to a client.
Specifies whether to allow, reject or switch to pass-through mode when an unknown HTTP method is parsed.

Specifies whether to attempt to execute a growphysical operation, if there is enough unused space on the device. A growphysical operation will be executed if there is at least 64 GB of free space, relative to the previous physical size of the affected VDO volume.
Specifies whether to automatically check for updates on the F5 Networks downloads server.
Specifies whether to automatically send phone home data to the F5 Networks PhoneHome server.
Specifies whether to enable Remote Triggered Black Hole RTBH of attacking IPs by advertising BGP routes.
Specifies whether to enable Traffic Scrubbing during attacks by advertising BGP routes.
Specifies whether to enable or disable intelligent selection of a back-end server pool.
Specifies whether to have the iRule code determine exactly when the FIX stream drops down to the ePVA hardware.
Specifies whether to perform certificate look up by IP address and port number.
Specifies whether to process client-side DNS packets with Recursion Desired set in the header.
Specifies whether to reassemble fragments.
Specifies whether to support server sack option in cookie response by default.
Specifies whether to support server timestamp option in cookie response by default.
Specifies whether to synchronize ASM configurations of device group members.
Specifies whether to use BigQuery's legacy SQL for this view .
Specifies whether to use IPComp encapsulation.
Specifies whether to use SSL Bridging.
Specifies whether you can use all the remaining disks in the disk group or not.
Specifies whether you want to block the TCP SackOK option from passing to the server on an initiating SYN.
Specifies whether you want to generate TCP sequence numbers on all SYNs that conform with RFC1948, and allow timestamp recycling.
Specifies whether you want to reset connections on timeout.
Specifies whether, upon receipt of an LDAP referral entry, the target follows (or chases) that referral.
Specifies which Ansible environment you're running this module within.
Specifies which GTM pool, for the system to use as the last resort pool for the wide IP.
Specifies which HTTP methods count as being known, removing RFC-defined methods from this list will cause the HTTP filter to not recognize them.
Specifies which NAT components to query.
Specifies which address family the prefix prefix belongs to
Specifies which application layer proxy is enabled for the virtual service.
Specifies which banner should be configured on the remote device.
Specifies which banner should be configured on the remote device. In Ansible 2.4 and earlier only login and motd were supported.
Specifies which banner should be configured on the remote device. In Ansible 2.8 and earlier only login and motd were supported.
Specifies which banner that should be configured on the remote device.
Specifies which banner that should be configured on the remote device. Value login indicates system login message prior to authenticating, motd is login announcement after successful authentication.
Specifies which context to target if you are running in the ASA in multiple context mode. Defaults to the current context you login to.
Specifies which controller will be the primary owner of the volume
Specifies which dataset properties should be queried in comma-separated format. For more information about dataset properties, check zfs(1M) man page.
Specifies which dataset properties should be queried in comma-separated format. For more information about dataset properties, check zpool(1M) man page.
Specifies which datasets types to display. Multiple values have to be provided in comma-separated form.
Specifies which days of the week the rule will be applied.
Specifies which email addresses receive alerts by email when notification_by_email is enabled.
Specifies which pool, as listed in Pool List, for the system to use as the last resort pool for the wide IP.
Specifies which version of IKE is used.
Specifies with address family the IP address belongs to
Specifies, yes, that the system uses the network measurements to set the optimal proxy buffer size.
Specifies, for IP traffic passing through the system to back-end servers, whether the system modifies the IP type-of-service (ToS) setting in an IP packet header.
Specifies, for IP traffic passing through the system to back-end servers, whether the system modifies the link quality-of-service (QoS) setting in an IP packet header.
Specifies, for IP traffic passing through the system to clients, whether the system modifies the IP type-of-service (ToS) setting in an IP packet header.
Specifies, for IP traffic passing through the system to clients, whether the system modifies the link quality-of-service (QoS) setting in an IP packet header.
Specifies, if you activate more than one health monitor, the number of health monitors that must receive successful responses in order for the link to be considered available.
Specifies, if you have enabled HTTPD access, the IP address or address range for other systems that can communicate with this system.
Specifies, if you have enabled SSH access, the IP address or address range for other systems that can use SSH to communicate with this system.
Specifies, in seconds, the frequency at which the system issues the monitor check when either the resource is down or the status of the resource is unknown.

Specifies, in seconds, the frequency at which the system issues the monitor check when either the resource is down or the status of the resource is unknown. When creating a new monitor, the default is 10.
Specifies, in seconds, the frequency at which the system issues the monitor check when the resource is up.
Specifies, in seconds, the length of time for which the persistence entry is valid.
Specifies, in seconds, the timeout value to discard long-lived sessions that do not have an active flow.
Specifies, once the trunk is configured, the policy that the trunk uses to determine which member link (interface) can handle new traffic.
Specifies, when enabled, that the system translates the address of the virtual server.
Specifies, when enabled, that the system translates the port of the virtual server.
Specifies, when yes, a FAST join, allowing data to be sent on the MP_JOIN_SYN, which can allow a server response to occur in parallel with the JOIN.
Specifies, when yes, significantly improved performance to Microsoft Windows and MacOS peers who are writing out on a very small send buffer.
Specifies, when yes, that IP Intelligence shun list events are logged.
Specifies, when yes, that connections in a TIME-WAIT state are reused when the system receives a SYN packet, indicating a request for a new connection.
Specifies, when yes, that remotely triggered blackholing events are logged.

Specifies, when yes, that the SSL profile performs unclean shutdowns of all SSL connections, which means that underlying TCP connections are closed without exchanging the required SSL shutdown alerts.
Specifies, when yes, that the next time you reboot the system, the system boots to an ISO image on the network, rather than an internal media drive.
Specifies, when yes, that the server sends responses to clients in the HTTP/1.0 format.
Specifies, when yes, that the server uses workarounds for HTTP 1.1 close issues.
Specifies, when yes, that the system accepts Multipath TCP (MPTCP) connections, which allow multiple client-side flows to connect to a single server-side flow.
Specifies, when yes, that the system activates an Application DoS iRule event.
Specifies, when yes, that the system advertises an option (such as time stamps) to the server only when the option is negotiated with the client.
Specifies, when yes, that the system attempts to advertise the same maximum segment size (MSS) to the server-side connection as that of the client-side connection.
Specifies, when yes, that the system calculates the checksum for MPTCP connections.
Specifies, when yes, that the system can actually communicate with the server before establishing a client connection.
Specifies, when yes, that the system defers allocation of the connection chain context until the system has received the payload from the client.
Specifies, when yes, that the system load balances UDP traffic packet-by-packet.
Specifies, when yes, that the system menu displays on the LCD screen on the front of the unit. This setting has no effect when used on the VE platform.
Specifies, when yes, that the system paces the egress packets to avoid dropping packets, allowing for optimum goodput.
Specifies, when yes, that the system processes data using a selective negative acknowledgment (SNACK) whenever possible, to improve system performance.
Specifies, when yes, that the system processes data using selective ACKs (SACKs) whenever possible, to improve system performance.
Specifies, when yes, that the system sends a reset packet (RST) in addition to deleting the connection, when a connection exceeds the idle timeout value.
Specifies, when yes, that the system supports TCP Fast Open, which reduces latency by allowing a client to include the first packet of data with the SYN
Specifies, when yes, that the system supports a Single Page Applications.

Specifies, when yes, that the system suppresses informational text on the console during the boot cycle. When no, the system presents messages and informational text on the console during the boot cycle.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses Slow-Start Congestion Avoidance as described in RFC3390 in order to ramp up traffic without causing excessive congestion on the link.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses Tail Loss Probe to reduce the number of retransmission timeouts.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses a cache for storing congestion metrics.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses early retransmit (as specified in RFC 5827) to reduce the recovery time for connections that are receive- buffer or user-data limited.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses limited transmit recovery revisions for fast retransmits (as specified in RFC 3042) to reduce the recovery time for connections on a lossy network.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses the TCP flags CWR (congestion window reduction) and ECE (ECN-Echo) to notify its peer of congestion and congestion counter-measures.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses the network measurements to set the optimal receive window size.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses the network measurements to set the optimal send buffer size.
Specifies, when yes, that the system uses the timestamps extension for TCP (as specified in RFC 1323) to enhance high-speed network performance.
Specifies, when yes, that the system verifies the checksum for MPTCP connections.

Specifies, when yes, that the system will not keep a steady-state maximum of connections to the back-end unless the number of connections to the pool have dropped beneath the minimum_pool_size specified in the profile.
Specifies, when yes, the use of the selective ACK (SACK) option to acknowledge duplicate segments.
Specifies, when yes, to use RFC2385 TCP-MD5 signatures to protect TCP traffic against intermediate tampering.
Specifies, when checked (enabled), that no DSS option is sent on the JOIN ACK.
Specifies, when checked (enabled), that the system can send fewer than one ACK (acknowledgment) segment per data segment received.
Specifies, when checked enabled, that the system accepts SSH communications.
Specifies, when enabled, that the SSL options setting (in OpenSSL) is set to all.

Specify an unknown unicast level in percent. The default value is 100%.

Specify source interface of BGP session and updates.

Specify subscription pool IDs to consume. Prefer over pool when possible as it is much faster. A pool ID may be specified as a string - just the pool ID (ex. 0123456789abcdef0123456789abcdef), or as a dict with the pool ID as the key, and a quantity as the value (ex. 0123456789abcdef0123456789abcdef: 2. If the quantity is provided, it is used to consume multiple entitlements from a pool (the pool must support this). Mutually exclusive with pool.
Specify tablets to be used as input devices
Specify that the virtual server uses the device NAT policy, as specified in the Firewall Options.

Specify the IP address advertised by BGP. The value is a string of 0 to 255 characters.

Specify the IP address in Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) format; address/prefix, where the prefix length is in bits. For example, for IPv4, 10.0.0.1/32 or 10.0.0.0/24, and for IPv6, ffe1::0020/64 or 2001:ed8:77b5:2:10:10:100:42/64.
Specify the IP address of the interface in x.x.x.x/n format.
Specify the IP address.

Specify the IPv4 filtering policy applied to the routes to be advertised to a specified peer. The value is a string of 1 to 169 characters.
Specify the Keepalive time of a peer or peer group. The value is an integer ranging from 0 to 21845. The default value is 60.
Specify the Keychain authentication name used when BGP peers establish a TCP connection. The value is a string of 1 to 47 case-insensitive characters.
Specify the KubeVirt API version.
Specify the LACP fallback mode as bundles or individual.

Specify the LACP mode.

Specify the LACP timeout as slow(30 seconds) or fast(4 seconds).
Specify the MAC address of the port.
